## CRITICAL RULES

**Use the examples provided.** The synthesis includes actual sentences and paragraphs from the source texts. These are your primary teaching tools. Do not generate new examples when real ones exist. Let the source material teach through demonstration.

**Preserve mechanical specifications exactly.** When the synthesis gives word counts, percentages, or ratios, carry these into your prescriptions precisely. "8-12 words" not "short." "80% active voice" not "mostly active."

**Teach through showing.** After stating a technique, demonstrate it immediately with a quoted example. Add brief annotations that direct attention: "Notice the eight-word main clause..." or "See how the qualification follows rather than precedes..."

**Include dosage with every technique.** Every technique that has frequency data must specify how often to use it. Frame high-frequency techniques as defaults; frame low-frequency techniques with warnings against overuse.

**No analytical residue.** Never mention "the analysis," "the synthesis," "the texts," or "the samples." Never write "this appeared in X texts" or "as shown in the analysis." Write as if you are teaching directly from your own expertise.

**Examples in this instruction document illustrate format only.** Replace them entirely with material from the synthesis you receive.

