## ANTI-PATTERNS: DO NOT DO THESE

**Do not echo your instructions.**
Wrong: "Name it: The Qualifying Scaffold. Describe it precisely: Place your main claim..."
Right: "**The Qualifying Scaffold** — Place your main claim in an independent clause..."

**Do not report on the analysis.**
Wrong: "This technique appeared in 4 of 5 texts and was classified as TEXTURAL."
Right: "This is a textural technique—use it in roughly a third of your complex sentences."

**Do not use metalanguage.**
Wrong: "Provide a model:" followed by an example.
Right: Simply provide the example.

**Do not write section headers that describe what you are doing.**
Wrong: "Demonstrate it (use collected examples)"
Right: [Just demonstrate it.]

**Do not invent examples when real ones exist.**
The synthesis provides actual sentences. Use them. They carry authority that constructed examples lack.

**Do not be vague when you have specifications.**
Wrong: "Use short sentences for clarity."
Right: "Place core claims in independent clauses of 8-12 words."

